# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: laptop
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:laptop/1-wire] 1-Wire is similar in concept to I2C, but with lower data rates and longer range.
[src:laptop/1-wire] It is typically used to communicate with small inexpensive devices such as digital thermometers and weather instruments.
[src:laptop/1-wire] A network of 1-Wire devices with an associated master device is called a **MicroLAN**.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The protocol is also used in small, 16 mm electronic keys known as a **Dallas key** or **iButton**.
[src:laptop/1-wire] One distinctive feature of the bus is the possibility of using only two conductors — data and ground.
[src:laptop/1-wire] To accomplish this, 1-Wire devices integrate a small capacitor (~800 pF) to store charge, which powers the device during periods when the data line is active.
[src:laptop/1-wire] 1-Wire devices are available in different packages: integrated circuits, a TO-92-style package (as typically used for transistors), and a portable form called an iButton or Dallas key which is a small stainless-steel package that resembles a watch battery.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Manufacturers also produce devices more complex than a single component that use the 1-Wire bus to communicate.
[src:laptop/1-wire] 1-Wire devices can fit in different places in a system.
[src:laptop/1-wire] It might be one of many components on a circuit board within a product.
[src:laptop/1-wire] It also might be a single component within a device such as a temperature probe.
[src:laptop/1-wire] It could be attached to a device being monitored.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Some laboratory systems connect to 1-Wire devices using cables with modular connectors or CAT-5 cable.
[src:laptop/1-wire] In such systems, RJ11 (6P2C or 6P4C modular plugs, commonly used for telephones) are popular.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Systems of sensors and actuators can be built by wiring together many 1-Wire components.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Each 1-Wire component contains all of the logic needed to operate on the 1-Wire bus.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Examples include temperature loggers, timers, voltage and current sensors, battery monitors, and memory.
[src:laptop/1-wire] These can be connected to a PC using a bus converter.
[src:laptop/1-wire] USB, RS-232 serial, and parallel port interfaces are popular solutions for connecting a MicroLan to the host PC.
[src:laptop/1-wire] 1-Wire devices can also be interfaced directly to microcontrollers from various vendors.
[src:laptop/1-wire] iButtons are connected to 1-Wire bus systems by means of sockets with contacts that touch the "lid" and "base" of the canister.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Alternatively, the connection can be semi-permanent with a socket into which the iButton clips, but from which it is easily removed.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Each 1-Wire chip has a unique identifier code.
[src:laptop/1-wire] This feature makes the chips, especially iButtons, suitable electronic keys.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Some uses include locks, burglar alarms, computer systems, manufacturer-approved accessories, time clocks and courier and maintenance keys for smart safes.
[src:laptop/1-wire] iButtons have been used as Akbil smart tickets for the public transport in Istanbul.
[src:laptop/1-wire] They can also run smartcard programs such as Java Card 2.0, as exemplified by the "Java Ring" of 1998.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Apple MagSafe- and MagSafe-2-connector–equipped power supplies, displays, and Mac laptops use the 1-Wire protocol to send and receive data to and from the connected Mac laptop, via the middle pin of the connector.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Data include power supply model, wattage, and serial number; and laptop commands to send full power, and illuminate the red or green light-emitting diodes in the connector.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Dell laptop power supplies use the 1-Wire protocol to send data via the third wire to the laptop computer about power, current and voltage ratings.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The laptop will then refuse charging if the adapter does not meet requirements.
[src:laptop/1-wire] In any MicroLan, there is always one master in overall charge, which may be a personal computer or a microcontroller.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The master initiates activity on the bus, simplifying the avoidance of collisions on the bus.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Protocols are built into the master's software to detect collisions.
[src:laptop/1-wire] After a collision, the master retries the required communication.
[src:laptop/1-wire] A 1-Wire network is a single open drain wire with a single pull-up resistor.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The pull-up resistor pulls the wire up to 3 or 5 volts.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The master device and all the slaves each have a single open-drain connection to drive the wire, and a way to sense the state of the wire.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Despite the "1-Wire" name, all devices must also have a second conductor for a ground connection to permit a return current to flow through the data wire.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Communication occurs when a master or slave briefly pulls the bus low, *i.e.*, connects the pull-up resistor to ground through its output MOSFET.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The data wire is high when idle, and so it can also power a limited number of slave devices.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Data rates of 16.3 kbit/s can be achieved.
[src:laptop/1-wire] There is also an overdrive mode that speeds up the communication by a factor of 10.
[src:laptop/1-wire] A short 1-Wire bus can be driven from a single digital I/O pin on a microcontroller.
[src:laptop/1-wire] A universal asynchronous receiver-transmitter (UART) can also be used.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Specific 1-Wire driver and bridge chips are available.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Universal Serial Bus "bridge" chips are also available.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Bridge chips are particularly useful to drive cables longer than 100 m.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Up to 300-meter twisted pairs, *i.e.*, telephone cables, have been tested by the manufacturer.
[src:laptop/1-wire] These extreme lengths require adjustments to the pull-up resistances from 5 to 1 kΩ.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The master starts a transmission with a *reset* pulse, which pulls the wire to 0 volts for at least 480 μs.
[src:laptop/1-wire] This resets every slave device on the bus.
[src:laptop/1-wire] After that, any slave device, if present, shows that it exists with a "presence" pulse: it holds the bus low for at least 60 μs after the master releases the bus.
[src:laptop/1-wire] To send a binary number "1", the bus master sends a very brief (1–15 μs) low pulse.
[src:laptop/1-wire] To send a binary number "0", the master sends a 60 μs low pulse.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The falling (negative) edge of the pulse is used to start a monostable multivibrator in the slave device.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The multivibrator in the slave reads the data line about 30 μs after the falling edge.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The slave's internal timer is an inexpensive analog timer.
[src:laptop/1-wire] It has analog tolerances that affect its timing accuracy.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Therefore, the pulses are calculated to be within margins.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Therefore, the "0" pulses have to be 60 μs long, and the "1" pulses can't be longer than 15 μs.
[src:laptop/1-wire] When receiving data, the master sends a 1–15 μs 0 volt pulse to start each bit.
[src:laptop/1-wire] If the transmitting slave unit wants to send a "1", it does nothing, and the bus goes to the pulled-up voltage.
[src:laptop/1-wire] If the transmitting slave wants to send a "0", it pulls the data line to ground for 60 μs.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The basic sequence is a reset pulse followed by an eight-bit command, and then data are sent or received in groups of eight bits.
[src:laptop/1-wire] When a sequence of data is being transferred, errors can be detected with an eight-bit CRC (weak data protection)..
[src:laptop/1-wire] Each device on the bus has a 64-bit serial number, of which eight bits are used as a checksum, thus allowing a "universe" of 256 (over 7.2 × 1016) unique device identities.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The least significant byte of the serial number is an eight-bit number that tells the type of the device.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The most significant byte is a standard (for the 1-Wire bus) eight-bit CRC.
[src:laptop/1-wire] There are several standard broadcast commands, as well as commands used to address a particular device.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The master can send a selection command, then the address of a particular device.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The next command is executed only by the addressed device.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The 1-Wire bus enumeration protocol, like other singulation protocols, is an algorithm the master uses to read the address of every device on the bus.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Since the address includes the device type and a CRC, recovering the roster of addresses also produces a reliable inventory of the devices on the bus.
[src:laptop/1-wire] To find the devices, the master broadcasts an enumeration command, and then an address, "listening" after each bit of an address.
[src:laptop/1-wire] If a slave's address matches all the address bits sent so far, it returns a 0.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The master uses this simple behavior to search systematically for valid sequences of address bits.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The process is much faster than a brute force search of all possible 56-bit numbers, because as soon as an invalid bit is detected, all subsequent address bits are known to be invalid.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The 56-bit address space is searched as a binary tree, allowing up to 75 devices to be found per second.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The order in which device addresses are discovered by this enumeration protocol is deterministic and depends only on the device type and serial number.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Bit-reversing these 56 bits yields the order of discovery for devices using Maxim's published algorithm (algorithm defined in Application Note 187).
[src:laptop/1-wire] The search algorithm can be implemented in an alternative form, initially searching paths with address bits equal to 1, rather than 0.
[src:laptop/1-wire] In this case, inverting the 56 address bits and then reversing them yields the order of discovery.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The location of devices on the bus is sometimes significant.
[src:laptop/1-wire] For these situations, a microcontroller can use several pins, or the manufacturer has a 1-Wire device that can switch the bus off or pass it on.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Software can therefore explore sequential *bus domains*.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Every 1-Wire device's 64-bit ROM ID ends with an 8-bit family code.
[src:laptop/1-wire] In most cases this byte is assigned to a single part number, so reading it from the bus is usually enough to identify the device—for example, 0x10 (DS18S20 thermometer), 0x01 (DS2401 silicon serial number), or 0x2D (DS2431 1 kbit EEPROM).
[src:laptop/1-wire] Various people have created online databases of family codes from the broad range of 1-Wire memory, authenticator, ID, and battery-monitor devices.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The following signals were generated by an FPGA, which was the master for the communication with a DS2432 (1 kbit EEPROM with SHA-1 Engine) chip, and measured with a logic analyzer.
[src:laptop/1-wire] A logic high on the 1-Wire output, means the output of the FPGA is in tri-state mode and the 1-Wire device can pull the bus low.
[src:laptop/1-wire] A low means the FPGA pulls down the bus.
[src:laptop/1-wire] The 1-Wire input is the measured bus signal.
[src:laptop/1-wire] On input sample time high, the FPGA samples the input for detecting the device response and receiving bits.
[src:laptop/1-wire] When developing and/or troubleshooting the 1-Wire bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:laptop/1-wire] Logic analyzers and bus analyzers are tools that collect, analyze, decode, and store signals to simplify viewing the high-speed waveforms.
[src:laptop/1080p] 1080p video signals are supported by ATSC standards in the United States and DVB standards in Europe.
[src:laptop/1080p] Applications of the 1080p standard include television broadcasts, Blu-ray Discs, smartphones, Internet content such as YouTube videos and Netflix TV shows and movies, consumer-grade televisions and projectors, computer monitors and video game consoles.
[src:laptop/1080p] Small camcorders, smartphones and digital cameras can capture still and moving images in 1080p resolution.
[src:laptop/1080p] Any display device that advertises 1080p typically refers to the ability to accept a 1080p signal and display it with a native resolution of at least 1080 lines vertically (as well as the ability to upscale lower-resolution material to 1080p).
[src:laptop/1080p] This means that the display is not over-scanning, under-scanning, or reinterpreting the signal to a lower resolution.
[src:laptop/1080p] The HD ready 1080p logo program, by DigitalEurope, requires that certified TV sets support 1080p 24 fps, 1080p 25 fps, 1080p 50 fps, and 1080p 60 fps formats, among other requirements, with fps meaning frames per second.
[src:laptop/1080p] For live broadcast applications, a high-definition progressive scan format operating at 1080p at 50 or 60 frames per second was being evaluated as a future standard for moving picture acquisition, although 24 fps was used for shooting movies.
[src:laptop/1080p] Most current revisions of SMPTE 372M, SMPTE 424M and EBU Tech 3299 require YCbCr color space and 4:2:2 chroma subsampling for transmitting 1080p50 (nominally 2.08 Gbit/s) and 1080p60 signal.
[src:laptop/1080p] In the United States, the original ATSC standards for HDTV supported 1080p video, but only at the frame rates of 23.976, 24, 25, 29.97 and 30 frames per second (colloquially known as **1080p24**, **1080p25** and **1080p30**).
[src:laptop/1080p] Such frame rates require H.264/AVC *High Profile Level 4.2*, while standard HDTV frame rates only require Level 4.0.
[src:laptop/1080p] This update is not expected to result in widespread availability of 1080p60 programming, since most of the existing digital receivers in use would only be able to decode the older, less-efficient MPEG-2 codec, and because there is a limited amount of bandwidth for subchannels.
[src:laptop/1080p] In Europe, 1080p25 signals have been supported by the DVB suite of broadcasting standards.
[src:laptop/1080p] The 1080p50 format is considered to be a future-proof production format and, eventually, a future broadcasting format.
[src:laptop/1080p] 1080p50 broadcasting should require the same bandwidth as 1080i50 signal and only 15–20% more than that of 720p50 signal due to increased compression efficiency, though 1080p50 production requires more bandwidth or more efficient codecs such as JPEG 2000, high-bitrate MPEG-2, or H.264/AVC and HEVC.
[src:laptop/1080p] EBU requires that legacy MPEG-4 AVC decoders should avoid crashing in the presence of SVC or 1080p50 (and higher resolution) packets.
[src:laptop/1080p] The ITU-T BT.2100 standard that includes Advanced 1080p video was subsequently published in July 2016.
[src:laptop/1080p] In practice, 1080p typically refers to a 1920 × 1080p raster with a 16:9 picture aspect ratio.
[src:laptop/1080p] The following is a list of other resolutions with a picture height of 1080 lines that are sometimes referred as 1080p.
[src:laptop/1080p] In the United States, 1080p over-the-air broadcasts are currently available in select stations in some cities in the US via ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations where as ATSC 3.0 is currently rolling out throughout the U.S.
[src:laptop/1080p] The majority of the stations that broadcast at 1080p are CBS and NBC stations and affiliates.
[src:laptop/1080p] All other stations do not broadcast at 1080p and usually broadcast at 720p60 (including when simulcasting in ATSC 3.0) or 1080i60 (outside of ATSC 3.0) encoded with MPEG-2.
[src:laptop/1080p] There is also technical restrictions with ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations that prevent stations from airing at 1080p.
[src:laptop/1080p] While converting to ATSC 3.0 is voluntary by TV Stations, there is no word when any of the major networks will consider airing at 1080p in the foreseeable future on a national scale, although they are required to broadcast ATSC signals for at least five years thereafter.
[src:laptop/1080p] However, satellite services (e.g., DirecTV, XstreamHD and Dish Network) use the 1080p/24-30 format with MPEG-4 AVC/H.264 encoding for pay-per-view movies that are downloaded in advance via satellite or on-demand via broadband.
[src:laptop/1080p] For material that originates from a progressive scanned 24 frame/s source (such as film), MPEG-2 lets the video be coded as 1080p24, irrespective of the final output format.
[src:laptop/1080p] These progressively-coded frames are tagged with metadata (literally, fields of the PICTURE header) instructing a decoder how to perform a 3:2 pulldown to interlace them.
[src:laptop/1080p] While the formal output of the MPEG-2 decoding process from such stations is 1080i60, the actual content is coded as 1080p24 and can be viewed as such (using a process known as inverse telecine) since no information is lost even when the broadcaster performs the 3:2 pulldown.
[src:laptop/1080p] In June 2016, German television stations began broadcasting 1080p50 high-definition video on eight channels via the HEVC-encoded DVB-T2 protocol.
[src:laptop/1080p] A total of 40 channels were available on March 29, 2017 (Phase 1).
[src:laptop/1080p] Blu-ray Discs are able to hold 1080p HD content, and most movies released on Blu-ray Disc produce a full 1080p HD picture when the player is connected to a 1080p HDTV via an HDMI cable.
[src:laptop/1080p] Generally this type of video runs at 30 to 40 megabits per second, compared to the 3.5 megabits per second for conventional standard definition broadcasts.
[src:laptop/1080p] Smartphones with 1080p Full HD display have been available on the market since 2012.
[src:laptop/1080p] As of 2014, it is the standard for mid-range to high-end smartphones, with many flagship devices using even higher resolutions, such as Quad HD (1440p) or Ultra HD (2160p).
[src:laptop/1080p] Several websites, including YouTube, allow videos to be uploaded in the 1080p format.
[src:laptop/1080p] YouTube streams 1080p content at approximately 4 megabits per second compared to Blu-ray's 30 to 40 megabits per second.
[src:laptop/1080p] Digital distribution services like Hulu and HBO Max also deliver 1080p content, such as movies available on Blu-ray Disc or from broadcast sources.
[src:laptop/1080p] This can include distribution services like peer-to-peer websites and public or private tracking networks.
[src:laptop/1080p] Netflix has been offering high quality 1080p content in the US and other countries through select internet providers since 2013.
[src:laptop/1080p] As of 2012, most consumer televisions being sold provide 1080p inputs, mainly via HDMI, and support full high-definition resolutions.
[src:laptop/1080p] 1080p resolution is available in all types of television, including plasma, LCD, DLP front and rear projection and LCD projection.
[src:laptop/1080p] For displaying film-based 1080i60 signals, a scheme called 3:2 pulldown reversal (reverse telecine) is beginning to appear in some newer 1080p displays, which can produce a true 1080p quality image from film-based 1080i60 programs.
[src:laptop/1080p] Similarly, 25fps content broadcast at 1080i50 may be deinterlaced to 1080p content with no loss of quality or resolution.
[src:laptop/1080p] AV equipment manufacturers have adopted the term *Full HD* to mean a set can display all available HD resolutions up to 1080p.
[src:laptop/1080p] The term is misleading, however, because it does not guarantee the set is capable of rendering digital video at all frame rates encoded in source files with 1920 X 1080 pixel resolution.
[src:laptop/1080p] Most notably, a "Full HD" set is not guaranteed to support the 1080p24 format, leading to consumer confusion.
[src:laptop/1080p] DigitalEurope (formerly EICTA) maintains the HD ready 1080p logo program that requires the certified TV sets to support 1080p24, 1080p50, and 1080p60, without overscan/underscan and picture distortion.
[src:laptop/1080p] Most widescreen cathode-ray tube (CRT) and liquid-crystal display (LCD) monitors can natively display 1080p content.
[src:laptop/1080p] For example, widescreen WUXGA monitors support 1920 × 1200 resolution, which can display a pixel for pixel reproduction of the 1080p (1920 × 1080) format.
[src:laptop/1080p] Additionally, many 23, 24, and 27-inch (690 mm) widescreen LCD monitors use 1920 × 1200 as their native resolution; 30 inch displays can display beyond 1080p at up to 2560 × 1600 (1600p).
[src:laptop/1080p] Many 27" monitors have native resolutions of 2560 × 1440 and hence operate at 1440p.
[src:laptop/1080p] Sony has their first and formerly Vaio 1080p laptop, VPCCB17FG, in 2011, and since Asus also has their first 4K laptop GL502 which was formerly branded Republic of Gamers in 2017, 1080p has also become the nowadays lowest standard for laptops.
[src:laptop/1080p] While Microsoft's original Xbox, launched as part of the sixth generation of video game consoles in 2001, could support a 1080i output in limited circumstances, support for 1080p began with the launch of the seventh generation of home video game consoles in 2005.
[src:laptop/1080p] Both the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 were capable of outputting at 1080p, with only the Wii unable to support the resolution.
[src:laptop/1080p] All home video game consoles launched as part of the eighth generation, which began in 2012 with the launch of the Wii U, were capable of 1080p outputs.
[src:laptop/1080p] Mid-generation hardware revisions and new models introduced by Sony and Microsoft to their respective PlayStation 4 and Xbox One consoles added the capability of outputting at 4K UHD — well beyond 1080p.
[src:laptop/1080p] Moreover, this mid-generational improvement in computing power also represented a leap in the ability of video game consoles to render gaming content at a 1080p resolution or higher, rather than relying on upscaling.
[src:laptop/1080p] This trend continued with the launch of the current ninth generation of video game consoles in 2020, in which both Sony's PlayStation 5 and Microsoft's Xbox Series X were advertised as including 8K UHD support.
[src:laptop/1080p] As of 2024, however, neither console yet supports outputting the standard and PlayStation 5 packaging no longer advertises the feature.
[src:laptop/1080p] The Nintendo Switch console displays in resolutions up to 1080p when docked, while the successor console, Nintendo Switch 2, displays in 1080p when undocked, and up to 4K when docked.
[src:laptop/1080p] Many cameras—professional and consumer still, action and video cameras, including DSLR cameras—and other devices with built-in cameras such as laptops, smartphones and tablet computers, can capture 1080p24, 1080p25, 1080p30 or 1080p60 video, often encoding it in progressive segmented frame format.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] A **19-inch rack** is a standardized frame or enclosure for mounting multiple electronic equipment modules.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Each module has a front panel that is 19 inches (482.6 mm) wide.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The 19 inch dimension includes the edges or *ears* that protrude from each side of the equipment, allowing the module to be fastened to the rack frame with screws or bolts.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Common uses include computer servers, telecommunications equipment and networking hardware, audiovisual production gear, professional audio equipment, and scientific equipment.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Equipment designed to be placed in a rack is typically described as **rack-mount**/**rack-mountable**, a **rack-mount instrument**, **rack-mounted system**, or **rack-mount chassis**.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The rack may include subracks or shelves.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The height of the mountable equipment is standardized as multiples of 1.75 inches (44.45 mm) or one *rack unit* or *U* (less commonly *RU*).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The industry-standard rack cabinet is 42U tall; however, many data centers have racks taller than this.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The term **relay rack** appeared first in the late 19th century, in the world of telephony.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] By 1911, the term was also being used in railroad signaling.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] There is little evidence that the dimensions of these early racks were standardized.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch rack format with rack units of 1.75 inches (44.45 mm) was established as a standard by AT&T around 1922 in order to reduce the space required for repeater and termination equipment in a telephone company central office.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The earliest repeaters from 1914 were installed in ad hoc fashion on shelves, in wooden boxes and cabinets.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Once serial production started, they were built into custom-made racks, one per repeater.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] But in light of the rapid growth of the toll network, the engineering department of AT&T undertook a systematic redesign, resulting in a family of modular factory-assembled panels all "designed to mount on vertical supports spaced 191⁄2 inches between centers.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] By 1934, it was an established standard with holes tapped for 12-24 screws with alternating spacings of 1.25 inches (31.75 mm) and 0.5 inches (12.70 mm).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch rack format has remained constant while the technology that is mounted within it has changed considerably and the set of fields to which racks are applied has greatly expanded.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch (482.6 mm) standard rack arrangement is widely used throughout the telecommunications, computing, audio, video, entertainment and other industries, though the Western Electric 23-inch standard, with holes on 1-inch (25.4 mm) centers, is still used in legacy ILEC/CLEC facilities.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Nineteen-inch racks in two-post or four-post form hold most equipment in enterprise data centers, Internet service provider facilities, and professionally designed corporate server rooms, although hyperscale computing typically use wider racks.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] They allow for dense hardware configurations without occupying excessive floor space or requiring shelving.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Nineteen-inch racks are also often used to house professional audio and video equipment, including amplifiers, effects units, interfaces, headphone amplifiers, and even small-scale audio mixers.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] A third common use for rack-mounted equipment is industrial power, control, and automation hardware.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Typically, a piece of equipment being installed has a front panel height 1⁄32 inch (0.031 in; 0.79 mm) less than the allotted number of Us.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Thus, a 1U rackmount computer is not 1.750 inches (44.5 mm) tall but is 1.719 inches (43.7 mm) tall.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] If *n* is the number of rack units, the ideal formula for panel height is *h* = 1.75*n* − 0.031 for calculating in inches, and *h* = 44.45*n* − 0.794 for calculating in millimeters.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] This gap allows a bit of room above and below an installed piece of equipment so it may be removed without binding on the adjacent equipment.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Originally, the mounting holes were tapped with a particular screw thread.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] When rack rails are too thin to tap, rivet nuts or other threaded inserts can be used, and when the particular class of equipment to be mounted is known in advance, some of the holes can be omitted from the mounting rails.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Threaded mounting holes in racks where the equipment is frequently changed are problematic because the threads can be damaged or the mounting screws can break off; both problems render the mounting hole unusable.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Tapping large numbers of holes that may never be used is expensive; nonetheless, tapped-hole racks are still in use, generally for hardware that rarely changes.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Examples include telephone exchanges, network cabling panels, broadcast studios and some government and military applications.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The tapped-hole rack was first replaced by clearance-hole (Round Hole, Round Unthreaded Holes, and Versa Rail) racks.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The holes are large enough to permit a bolt to be freely inserted through without binding, and bolts are fastened in place using cage nuts.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] In the event of a nut being stripped out or a bolt breaking, the nut can be easily removed and replaced with a new one.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Production of clearance-hole racks is less expensive.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The next innovation in rack design has been the square-hole rack.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Square-hole racks allow boltless mounting, such that the rack-mount equipment only needs to insert through and hook down into the lip of the square hole.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Installation and removal of hardware in a square-hole rack is very easy and boltless, where the weight of the equipment and small retention clips are all that is necessary to hold the equipment in place.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Older equipment meant for round-hole or tapped-hole racks can still be used, with the use of cage nuts made for square-hole racks.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable equipment is traditionally mounted by bolting or clipping its front panel to the rack.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Within the IT industry, it is common for network/communications equipment to have multiple mounting positions, including tabletop and wall mounting, so rack-mountable equipment will often feature L-brackets that must be screwed or bolted to the equipment prior to mounting in a 19-inch rack.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] With the prevalence of 23-inch racks in the Telecoms industry, the same practice is also common, but with equipment having 19-inch and 23-inch brackets available, enabling them to be mounted in existing racks.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] A key structural weakness of front-mounted support is the bending stress placed on the mounting brackets of the equipment and the rack itself.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] As a result, 4-post racks have become common, featuring a mirrored pair of rear mounting posts.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Servers and deep pieces of equipment are often mounted using rails that are bolted to the front and rear posts (as above, it is common for such rails to have an adjustable depth), allowing the equipment to be supported by four posts, while also enabling it to be easily installed and removed.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] This, of course, varies by manufacturer, the design of the rack and its purpose, but through common constraining factors (such as raised-floor tile dimensions), these dimensions have become quite common.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The extra width and depth enable cabling to be routed with ease (also helping to maintain the minimum bend radius for fiber and copper cables) and deeper equipment to be utilized.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] A common feature in IT racks is mounting positions for *zero-U* accessories, such as power distribution units (PDUs) and vertical cable managers and ducts, that utilize the space between the rear rails and the side of the rack enclosure.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The strength required of the mounting posts means they are invariably not merely flat strips but actually a wider folded strip arranged around the corner of the rack.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The posts are usually made of steel of around 2 mm thickness (the official standard recommends a minimum of 1.9 mm), or of slightly thicker aluminum.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Racks, especially two-post racks, are often secured to the floor or adjacent building structure so as not to fall over.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] This is usually required by local building codes in seismic zones.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] According to Telcordia Technologies Generic Requirements document GR-63-CORE, during an earthquake, telecommunications equipment is subjected to motions that can over-stress the equipment framework, circuit boards, and connectors.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The amount of motion and resulting stress depends on the structural characteristics of the building and framework in which the equipment is contained and the severity of the earthquake.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Seismic racks rated according to GR-63, *NEBS Requirements: Physical Protection,* are available, with Zone 4 representing the most demanding environment.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] GR-3108, *Generic Requirements for Network Equipment in the Outside Plant (OSP),* specifies the usable opening of seismic-compliant 19-inch racks.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Heavy equipment or equipment that is commonly accessed for servicing, for which attaching or detaching at all four corners simultaneously would pose a problem, is often not mounted directly onto the rack but instead is mounted via rails (or slides).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] A pair of rails is mounted directly onto the rack, and the equipment then slides into the rack along the rails, which support it.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] When in place, the equipment may also then be bolted to the rack.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The rails may also be able to fully support the equipment in a position where it has been slid clear of the rack; this is useful for inspection or maintenance of equipment, which will then be slid back into the rack.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Some rack slides even include a tilt mechanism allowing easy access to the top or bottom of rack-mounted equipment when it is fully extended from the rack.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] A rails kit may include a cable management arm (CMA), which folds the cables attached to the server and allows them to expand neatly when the server is slid out, without being disconnected.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] When there is a large number of computers in a single rack, it is impractical for each one to have its own separate keyboard, mouse, and monitor.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Instead, a KVM switch or LOM software is used to share a single keyboard/video/mouse set amongst many different computers.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Since the mounting hole arrangement is vertically symmetric, it is possible to mount rack-mountable equipment upside-down.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] However, not all equipment is suitable for this type of mounting.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] For instance, most optical disc players will not work upside-down because the driving motor mechanism does not grip the disc.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] A standard 19-inch server rack cabinet is typically 42u in height, 600 millimetres (24 in) wide, and 36 inches (914.40 mm) deep.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] This comprises a volume of 974 L, or just under a cubic meter.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Newer server rack cabinets come with adjustable mounting rails, allowing the user to place the rails at a shorter depth if needed.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] There are a multitude of specialty server racks, including soundproof server racks, air-conditioned server racks, NEMA-rated, seismic-rated, open frame, narrow, and even miniature 19-inch racks for smaller applications.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Cabinets are generally sized to be no wider than the standard 24-inch-wide (610 mm) floor tiles used in most data centers.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Racks carrying telecom equipment like routers and switches often have extra width to accommodate the many cables on the sides.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] 19-inch equipment that needs to be moved often or protected from harsh treatment can be housed in a *road case* approved by the Air Transport Association of America (ATA), sometimes also referred to as a *flight case*.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Road cases typically have plywood sides laminated with polyvinyl chloride (PVC), extruded aluminum edges, steel corners, handles, and latches.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Larger cases typically have wheels for easy transport.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Road case racks come in different heights based on the 1U standard and different depths.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Non-isolated cases simply mount 19-inch mounting posts inside the case.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] To protect equipment from shock and vibration, road rack cases use an inner and outer case.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] These cases can be isolated by thick layers of foam or may use spring-loaded shock mounting.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Touring musicians, theatrical productions and sound and light companies use road case racks.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Rack strips used for road cases come in 2 types: single angle and double angle.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Double-angle rack strips offer better structural strength and an additional mounting face for cable management or additional support for heavy equipment.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] In 1965, a durable fiber-reinforced plastic 19-inch rackmount case was patented by ECS Composites and became widely used in military and commercial applications for electronic deployment and operation.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Rackmount cases are also constructed of thermo-stamped composite, carbon fiber, and DuPont's Kevlar for military and commercial uses.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Portable rack cases using a rotary-molded polyethylene outer shell are a lower-cost alternative to the more durable ATA-approved case.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] These cases are marketed to musicians and entertainers for equipment not subject to frequent transportation and rough handling.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The polyethylene shell is not fiberglass reinforced and is not rigid.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The shape of small cases is maintained by the rack rails and the cover seal extrusions alone.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Larger cases are further reinforced with additional plywood or sheet metal.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The outer shell is frequently embossed in a self-mating pattern to combat the tendency for stacked cases to deform slightly, creating a slope that encourages the upper case to slide off.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The cases typically use extruded aluminum bands at the ends of the body with tongue-and-groove mating to like bands for the covers.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] End covers are typically secured with either a simple draw latch or a rotary cam *butterfly* latch, named for the shape of the twist handle.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] There is no standard for airflow and cooling of rack-mounted equipment.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] A variety of airflow patterns can be found, including front intakes and rear exhausts, as well as side intakes and exhausts.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Low-wattage devices may not employ active cooling, but use only passive thermal radiation and convection to dissipate heat.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] For rack-mounted computer servers, devices generally intake air on the front and exhaust on the rear.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] This prevents circular airflows where hot exhaust air is recirculated through an adjacent device and causes overheating.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Although open-frame racks are the least expensive, they also expose air-cooled equipment to dust, lint, and other environmental contamination.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] An enclosed sealed cabinet with forced air fans permits air filtration to protect equipment from dust.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Large server rooms will often group rack cabinets together so that racks on both sides of an aisle are either front-facing or rear-facing, which simplifies cooling by supplying cool air to the front of the racks and collecting hot air from the rear of the racks.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] These aisles may themselves be enclosed in a cold air containment tunnel so that cooling air does not travel to other parts of the building where it is not needed or mixes with hot air, making it less efficient.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Raised or false floor cooling in server rooms can serve a similar purpose; they permit cooling airflow to equipment through the underfloor space to the underside of enclosed rack cabinets.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] A difficulty with forced air fan cooling in rack equipment is that fans can fail due to age or dust.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The fans themselves can be difficult to replace.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] In the case of network equipment, it may be necessary to unplug 50 or more cables from the device, remove the device from the rack, and then disassemble the device chassis to replace the fans.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] However, some rack equipment has been designed to make fan replacement easy, using quick-change fan trays that can be accessed without removing the cabling or the device from the rack, and in some cases without turning off the device so that operation is uninterrupted during replacement.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] A rack's mounting fixture consists of two parallel metal strips (also referred to as *posts* or *panel mounts*) standing vertically.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The posts are each 0.625 inches (15.88 mm) wide, and are separated by a gap of 17.75 inches (450.85 mm), giving an overall rack width of 19 inches (482.60 mm).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The posts have holes in them at regular intervals, with both posts matching, so that each hole is part of a horizontal pair with a center-to-center distance of 18.28–18.34 inches (464.2–465.8 mm).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The holes in the posts are arranged vertically in repeating sets of three, with center-to-center separations of 0.5, 0.625, 0.625 inches (12.70, 15.88, 15.88 mm).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The hole pattern thus repeats every 1.75 inches (44.45 mm).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Holes so arranged can either be tapped (usually 10-32 UNF thread, or, less often, 6mm metric) or have square holes for cage nuts.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Racks are vertically divided into regions, 44.45 millimetres (1.75 in) in height.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Each region has three complete hole pairs on each side.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The holes are centered at 6.35 millimetres (0.25 in), 22.25 millimetres (0.88 in), and 38.1 millimetres (1.50 in) from the top or bottom of the region.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Such a region is commonly known as a **U**, for *unit*, **RU** for *rack unit* or, in German, **HE**, for *Höheneinheit*.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Heights within racks are measured by this unit.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable equipment is usually designed to occupy some integer number of U.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] For example, an oscilloscope might be 4U high.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable computers and servers are mostly between 1U and 4U high.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] A blade server enclosure might require 10U.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Occasionally, one may see fractional U devices, such as a 1.5U server or devices that are just 22.5 or 15 cm in width, allowing for 2 or 3 such devices to be installed side by side, but these are much less common.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The height of a rack can vary from a few inches, such as in a broadcast console, to a floor-mounted rack whose interior is 45 rack units (200.2 centimetres or 78.82 inches) high.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Many wall-mounted enclosures for industrial equipment use 19-inch racks.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Some telecommunications and networking equipment is available in a narrower 10-inch format with the same unit height as a standard 19-inch rack.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] This standard is also gaining in popularity with hobbyists with limited space at their disposal.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Frames for holding rotary-dial telephone equipment, such as step-by-step telephone switches, were generally 11 feet 6 inches (3.51 m) high.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] A series of studies led to the adoption of frames 7 feet (2.1 m) high, with modular widths in multiples of 1 foot 1 inch (0.33 m)—most often 2 feet 2 inches (0.66 m) wide.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The **ETSI rack** is defined by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETS 300 119).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The distance of the right edge of the right mounting rail to the left edge of the left mounting rail is 535 millimetres (21.1 in).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] As 535 mm is very close to 21 inches, these racks are sometimes called *21-inch racks*.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The gap between the posts is 500 millimetres (19.69 in).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] As 19-inch equipment has a maximum width of 17+1⁄4 inches (438.15 mm), they can easily be mounted in an ETSI rack by means of an ETSI bracket or adapter plate.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] In contrast to the 19-inch standards, ETSI also defined the size of the rack enclosure: the four allowed widths are 150, 300, 600, 900 millimetres (5.9, 11.8, 23.6, 35.4 in) and two allowed depths are 300 and 600 millimetres (12 and 24 in).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Hole spacing is 25 millimetres (0.98 in).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] A 23-inch (580 mm) rack is used for housing telephone (primarily), computer, audio and other equipment – although it is less common than the 19-inch rack.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The size denotes the width of the faceplate for the installed equipment.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The rack unit is a measure of vertical spacing and is common to both the 19 and 23-inch racks.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Hole spacing is either on 1-inch (25 mm) centers (Western Electric standard), or the same as for 19-inch (482.6 mm) racks (0.625 in or 15.9 mm spacing).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Open Rack is a mounting system designed by the Open Compute Project that has the same outside dimensions as typical 19-inch racks (e.g., 600 mm width), but internally supports wider equipment modules of 547 millimetres (21.5 in).
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] OpenVPX is an industry standard for modules that can be installed in a chassis in defense applications.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The modules can provide a variety of functions, similar to equipment in a rack.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Eurorack is a standard generally used in electronic music production to install components of a modular synthesizer, an electronic music instrument.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] This is achieved with a rack mounting system specific to the standard.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Eurocard is an IEEE standard format for printed circuit board (PCB) cards that can be plugged together into a standard chassis, which, in turn, can be mounted in a 19-inch rack.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] The chassis consists of a series of slotted card guides on the top and bottom, into which the cards are slid so they stand on end, like books on a shelf.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] At the spine of each card is one or more connectors which plug into mating connectors on a backplane that closes the rear of the chassis.
[src:laptop/19-inch-rack] Several standards such as VMEbus (Versa Module Eurocard bus), STEbus, PCI eXtensions for Instrumentation, openGear and others were developed, which share goals with Eurocard.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] A **2-in-1 laptop**, also known as a **convertible laptop**, **2-in-1 PC**, **2-in-1 tablet**, **laplet**, **tabtop**, **laptop tablet**, or simply **2-in-1**, is a portable computer that has features of both tablets and laptops.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] 2-in-1 PCs consist of portable computer components within light and thin chassis, and exemplify technological convergence.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] They are convenient for media consumption and non-intensive tasks in tablet mode yet useful for content creation in laptop mode.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Both pre-2-in-1 convertibles and hybrids were crossover devices that combined features of both tablets and laptops.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] The later 2-in-1 PCs comprise a category that is a sibling to both the pre-2-in-1 convertibles and hybrids.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Rotational-convertible format is where in addition to the conventional hinging action, the central single hinge mechanism is also able to rotate about a central axis perpendicular to the keyboard surface, such that the laptop can be turned into a thick tablet.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Most netvertibles have the option to support active (electromagnetic) stylus and/or touchscreen (resistive or capacitive), some being ruggedized such as Panasonic Toughbook CF series.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Other examples include Toshiba Portege M7xx, Fujitsu LifeBook T series and HP EliteBook Revolve series.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] When connected to the keyboard, the display of the detachable can either be free-standing on the hinge or require external support, often in the form of a kickstand.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Novel ways of providing external support include the bending frame and locking mechanism of the HP Spectre x2.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Though the keyboard is usually bundled with the purchase of a 2-in-1 detachable, it is occasionally deemed an optional accessory by manufacturers in order to minimize the starting price of a device.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] In such cases the 2-in-1 detachable is often displayed with its complementary keyboard in advertisements and promotional materials.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] This is true for all devices of the Surface and Surface Pro lines.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Operating systems such as Android even show the mouse cursor when a mouse is connected to a device running it, whereas Ubuntu Touch takes it even further by allowing the user to change the UI to a typical desktop environment which allows for desktop level multitasking, albeit with a smaller display.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] 2-in-1s fall in the category of hybrid or convertible tablets but are distinct in that they run a full-featured desktop operating system and have I/O ports typically found on laptops, such as USB and DisplayPort.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] The most prominent element is the keyboard that allows the 2-in-1 to provide the ergonomic typing experience of a laptop.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] While 2-in-1s fall in a category distinct from laptops, they loosely parallel the traits of the Ultrabook device category, having light and thin chassis, power-efficient CPUs, and long battery lives.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] They are distinguished from traditional Ultrabooks by the inclusion of a touchscreen display and a concealable or detachable keyboard.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] The earliest device that can be considered a 2-in-1 detachable is the Compaq Concerto from 1993.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] It came with Windows 3.1 and Windows for Pen Computing, and had a cabled detachable keyboard, and battery powered stylus.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] In June 1994, IBM introduced the ThinkPad 360P, which features a display that can be rotated backwards and closed down into a pen-operated tablet.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Mainstream attention for 2-in-1 PCs was not achieved until nearly two decades later, when many manufactures showed devices, at that time referred to as "hybrid" devices, at CES 2011.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] While Packard Bell, Acer and HP all had Microsoft Windows based 2-in-1s by 2011, Lenovo released the well reviewed Windows 2-in-1: The X220 Tablet variant of the ThinkPad X220, successor of 2010's ThinkPad X201 Tablet.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] The 12-inch device included a digital stylus housed within the chassis, somewhat ruggedized construction, and a multi-touch screen with a twist and fold hinge.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Microsoft started its own line of 2-in-1s with the introduction of the Surface Pro series, the first of which was released in February 2013.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] It had a 10.6-inch (27 cm) display, Intel Core i5 CPU, and included the Pro Pen stylus and a detachable keyboard that doubled as a protective screen cover.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] In 2015 Microsoft introduced the Surface Book series, which, similar to the Surface Pro series, features a detachable keyboard cover and Surface Pen stylus.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Samsung entered the 2-in-1 PC market with the release of the Windows-based Samsung Galaxy TabPro S, which was released in March 2016.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] It had a 12-inch display, Intel Core m3 CPU, a first-party keyboard attachment, and a TabPro Pen.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Its successor, the Galaxy Book, was released in February 2017.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Coming in a 10.6-inch model and a 12-inch model, the Galaxy Book has an improved detachable keyboard and include an S Pen.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Google entered the 2-in-1 market after it announced the Pixel Slate in October 2018.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] It runs on ChromeOS and features a 12.3-inch display.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] It includes two USB-C ports, but it omits the 3.5mm headphone jack.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] The featured Pixel Keyboard and Pixelbook Pen are sold separately.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Since 2012, a number of other prominent laptop manufacturers, such as Dell, Asus, and Sony have also begun releasing their own 2-in-1s.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] While the iPad Pro has optional Smart Keyboard and Apple Pencil accessories, Apple has yet to release a true 2-in-1 PC in a detachable form-factor and with a similar desktop OS, citing the quote below.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] 2-in-1s are natively supported by the Microsoft Windows, and Google ChromeOS operating systems.
[src:laptop/2-in-1-convertible] Various other Linux distributions also support some touch features of 2-in-1s, though they are generally unsupported by hardware vendors.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A **laptop** is a portable personal computer (PC).
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Laptops typically have a clamshell form factor with a flat-panel screen on the inside of the upper lid and an alphanumeric keyboard and pointing device on the inside of the lower lid.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Most of the computer's internal hardware is in the lower part, under the keyboard, although many modern laptops have a built-in webcam at the top of the screen, and some even feature a touchscreen display.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] In most cases, unlike tablet computers which run on mobile operating systems, laptops tend to run on desktop operating systems, which were originally developed for desktop computers.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Laptops are used in a variety of settings, such as at work (especially on business trips), in education, for playing games, content creating, web browsing, for personal multimedia, and for general home computer use.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] They can be powered using either continuous wall power or a rechargeable battery, and can be folded shut for convenient storage and transportation, making them suitable for mobile use.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Laptops feature all the standard input and output components of a desktop computer in a single compact unit, including a display screen (usually 11–17 in or 280–430 mm in diagonal size), speakers, a keyboard, and a pointing device (usually a trackpad).
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Hardware specifications vary significantly between different types, models, and price points.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Design elements, form factors, and construction can also vary significantly between models depending on intended use.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Examples of specialized models of laptops include 2-in-1 laptops, with keyboards that either be detached or pivoted out of view from the display (often marketed having a "laptop mode"), and rugged laptops, for use in construction or military applications.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Portable computers, which later developed into modern laptops, were originally considered to be a small niche market, mostly for specialized field applications, such as in the military, for accountants, or travelling sales representatives.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] As portable computers evolved into modern laptops, they became widely used for a variety of purposes.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The history of the laptop follows closely behind the development of the personal computer itself.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A "personal, portable information manipulator" was imagined by Alan Kay at Xerox PARC in 1968, and described in his 1972 paper as the "Dynabook".
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The IBM Special Computer APL Machine Portable (SCAMP) was demonstrated in 1973.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] This prototype was based on the IBM PALM processor.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The IBM 5100, the first commercially available portable computer, appeared in September 1975, and was based on the SCAMP prototype.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] As 8-bit CPU machines became widely accepted, the number of portables increased rapidly.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The first "laptop-sized notebook computer" was the Epson HX-20, invented (patented) by Suwa Seikosha's Yukio Yokozawa in July 1980, introduced at the COMDEX computer show in Las Vegas by Japanese company Seiko Epson in 1981, and released in July 1982.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] It had an LCD screen, a rechargeable battery, and a calculator-size printer, in a 1.6 kg (3.5 lb) chassis, the size of an A4 notebook.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] It was described as a "laptop" and "notebook" computer in its patent.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Both Tandy/RadioShack and Hewlett-Packard (HP) also produced portable computers of varying designs during this period.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The first laptops using the flip form factor appeared in the early 1980s.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The Dulmont Magnum was released in Australia in 1981–82, but was not marketed internationally until 1984–85.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The US$8,150 (equivalent to $27,190 in 2025) GRiD Compass 1101, released in 1982, was used at NASA and by the military, among others.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The Sharp PC-5000, the Ampere WS-1, and Gavilan SC were released between 1983 and 1985.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The Toshiba T1100 won acceptance by PC experts and the mass market as a way to have PC portability.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] From 1983 onward, several new input techniques were developed and included in laptops, including the touch pad (Gavilan SC, 1983), the pointing stick (IBM ThinkPad 700, 1992), and handwriting recognition (Linus Write-Top, 1987).
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Some CPUs, such as the 1990 Intel i386SL, were designed to use minimum power to increase the battery life of portable computers and were supported by dynamic power management features such as Intel SpeedStep and AMD PowerNow! in some designs.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Some laptops in the 1980s using red plasma displays could only be used when connected to AC power, and had a built in power supply.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The development of memory cards was driven in the 1980s by the need for a floppy-disk-drive alternative, having lower power consumption, less weight, and reduced volume in laptops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The Personal Computer Memory Card International Association (PCMCIA) was an industry association created in 1989 to promote a standard for memory cards in PCs.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The specification for PCMCIA type I cards, later renamed PC Cards, was first released in 1990.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Displays reached 640x480 (VGA) resolution by 1988 (Compaq SLT/286), and color screens started becoming a common upgrade in 1991, with increases in resolution and screen size occurring frequently until the introduction of 17" screen laptops in 2003.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Hard drives started to be used in portables, encouraged by the introduction of 3.5" drives in the late 1980s, and became common in laptops starting with the introduction of 2.5" and smaller drives around 1990; capacities have typically lagged behind those of physically larger desktop drives.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] By 1992 the laptop market was growing about three times faster than that of desktops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] By 1994 laptops were also more profitable than desktops, and accounted for one sixth of the personal computer market, up from one twentieth in 1990.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] They were so important that Dell risked, experts said, "second-rate status" in the industry for not having a strong laptop product line.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Optical disc drives became common in full-size laptops around 1997: initially these were CD-ROM drives, and these later included writable and higher capacity formats like DVD and Blu-Ray.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Starting around 2011, the trend shifted against internal optical drives, and as of 2022, they have largely disappeared, though are still readily available as external peripherals.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Resolutions of laptop webcams have climbed over time, from VGA-resolution to 1080p or even higher on some newer models.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The earliest-known laptops with 1080p (Full HD) webcams, like the Samsung 700G7C, were released in the early 2010s.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The word *laptop*, modeled after the term *desktop* (as in *desktop computer*), refers to the fact that the computer can be practically placed on the user's lap.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] As of 2024, in American English, the terms *laptop* and *notebook* are used interchangeably; in other dialects of English, one or the other may be preferred.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The term *notebook* originally referred to a type of portable computer that was smaller and lighter than mainstream laptops of the time - approximately similar in size to a paper notebook - but has since come to mean the same thing and no longer refers to any particular size.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The terms *laptop* and *notebook* trace their origins to the early 1980s, coined to describe portable computers in a size class smaller than the mainstream units (so-called "luggables") but larger than pocket computers.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The etymologist William Safire traced the origin of *laptop* to some time before 1984; the earliest attestation of *laptop* found by the *Oxford English Dictionary* dates to 1983.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The word is modeled after the term *desktop*, as in *desktop computer*.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] *Notebook*, meanwhile, emerged earlier in 1982 to describe Epson's HX-20 portable, whose dimensions roughly correspond to a letter-sized pad of paper.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Notebooks emerged as their own separate market from laptops with the release of the NEC UltraLite in 1988.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Notebooks and laptops continued to occupy distinct market segments into the mid-1990s, but ergonomic considerations and customer preference for larger screens soon led to notebooks converging with laptops in the late 1990s.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Now, the terms *laptop* and *notebook* are synonymous, with any preference between the two being a variation in dialect.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Since the 1970s introduction of portable computers, their forms have changed significantly, resulting in a variety of visually and technologically differing subclasses.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Excepting distinct legal trademark around terms (notably Ultrabook), hard distinctions between these classes were rare, and their usage has varied over time and between sources.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Since the late 2010s, more specific terms have become less commonly used, with sizes distinguished largely by the size of the screen.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] All of these terms have fallen out of favor as the size of mainstream laptops has gone down and their capabilities have gone up; except for niche models, laptop sizes tend to be distinguished by the approximate size of the screen (e.g.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] "13-inch" or "16-inch"), and for more powerful models, by any specialized purpose the machine is intended for, such as a "gaming laptop" or a "mobile workstation" for professional use.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A mobile workstation, also known as a desktop-replacement computer, is a type of laptop that is significantly more powerful—and generally more expensive—than a standard laptop computer.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] They are generally intended for professional use and to serve as desktop replacements.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Because of their high performance, however, they also have poorer battery life than most other laptops and require additional cooling systems.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Examples of mobile workstations include the Thinkpad P-series and the HP ZBook line.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A gaming laptop is a type of laptop that is primarily used to play video games.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Like mobile workstations, they are more powerful than standard laptops, but gaming laptops tend to prioritize features like a high refresh rate, a GPU that supports ray tracing, and RGB lighting.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Examples of gaming laptops include the Lenovo Legion series and Alienware laptops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The latest trend of technological convergence in the portable computer industry spawned a broad range of devices, which combined features of several previously separate device types.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The *hybrids*, *convertibles*, and *2-in-1s* emerged as crossover devices, which share traits of both tablets and laptops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] All such devices have a touchscreen display designed to allow users to work in a *tablet* mode, using either multi-touch gestures or a stylus/digital pen.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Convertibles are devices with the ability to conceal a hardware keyboard.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Keyboards on such devices can be flipped, rotated, or slid behind the back of the chassis, thus transforming from a laptop into a tablet.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] *Hybrids* have a keyboard detachment mechanism, and due to this feature, all critical components are situated in the part with the display.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] *2-in-1s* can have a hybrid or a convertible form, often dubbed *2-in-1 detachable* and *2-in-1 convertibles* respectively, but are distinguished by the ability to run a desktop OS, such as Windows 10.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] 2-in-1s are often marketed as *laptop replacement tablets*.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] As with nearly all of these distinctions, they are marketing terms first and technical distinctions secondarily, and vendors are not consistent in using a single name for a given type of device.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] 2-in-1s are often very thin, around 10 millimetres (0.39 in), and light devices with a long battery life.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] 2-in-1s are distinguished from mainstream tablets as they feature an x86-architecture CPU (typically a low- or ultra-low-voltage model), such as the Intel Core i5, run a full-featured desktop OS like Windows 10, and have a number of typical laptop I/O ports, such as USB 3 and Mini DisplayPort.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] 2-in-1s are designed to be used not only as a media consumption device but also as valid desktop or laptop replacements, due to their ability to run *desktop* applications, such as Adobe Photoshop.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] It is possible to connect multiple peripheral devices, such as a mouse, keyboard, and several external displays to a modern 2-in-1.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Microsoft Surface Pro-series devices and Surface Book are examples of modern 2-in-1 detachable, whereas Lenovo Yoga-series computers are a variant of 2-in-1 convertibles.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] While the older Surface RT and Surface 2 have the same chassis design as the Surface Pro, their use of ARM processors and Windows RT do not classify them as 2-in-1s, but as hybrid tablets.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] An ultraportable refers to a laptop that is smaller in size than other, contemporary laptops, although as the size and weight of mainstream laptops has decreased the significance of this and other size-specific terms has declined.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Examples of ultraportable laptops include the early MacBook Air and the Thinkpad X-series..
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A netbook was a marketing category for small, inexpensive laptops that were sold between 2007 and the early 2010s.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] These were small, had generally low performance, often based on the Intel Atom architecture, and were intended for basic tasks like web browsing and document viewing.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Examples of netbooks include the Asus Eee PC line and the Dell Inspiron Mini.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The term *netbook* is no longer actively being used to market small laptops, although similar models remain available; smaller Chromebooks, running Google's ChromeOS, also occupy a similar market niche.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A rugged laptop, or rugged computer, is designed to reliably operate in harsh usage conditions such as strong vibrations, extreme temperatures, and wet or dusty environments.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Rugged laptops are bulkier, heavier, and much more expensive than regular laptops, and thus are seldom seen in regular consumer use.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The basic components of laptops function identically to their desktop counterparts.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Traditionally they were miniaturized and adapted to mobile use, The design restrictions on power, size, and cooling of laptops limit the maximum performance of laptop parts compared to that of desktop components, although that difference has increasingly narrowed.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Most laptop components are not intended to be replaceable or upgradable by the end-user, except for components that can be detached; in the past, batteries and optical drives were commonly exchangeable.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] In the past, many laptops featured socketed processors but since 2015 virtually all laptops use processors that are soldered to the motherboard.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Many laptops come with RAM that is soldered to the motherboard and cannot be easily replaced.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] This restriction is one of the major differences between laptops and desktop computers, because the large "tower" cases used in desktop computers are designed so that new motherboards, hard disks, sound cards, RAM, and other components can be added.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Memory and storage can often be upgraded with some disassembly, but with the most compact laptops, there may be no upgradeable components at all.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The following sections summarize the differences and distinguishing features of laptop components in comparison to desktop personal computer parts.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The typical laptop has a screen in a clamshell form factor that when unfolded is upright to the user.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Detachables typically use a kickstand to stay upright.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Laptop screens most commonly use liquid-crystal display (LCD) technology, although OLED panels are becoming increasingly popular.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The display interfaces with the motherboard using the embedded DisplayPort protocol via the Low-voltage differential signaling (LVDS) 30 or 40 pin connector.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Earlier laptops use the FPD-Link standard.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The panels are mainly manufactured by AU Optronics, BOE Technology, LG Display or Samsung Display.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Externally, it can be a *glossy* or a *matte* (anti-glare) screen.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] As of 2021, mainstream consumer laptops tend to range between with 13" and 16" screens.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Larger and smaller models are available, but less common – there is no clear dividing line in minimum or maximum size.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Machines small enough to be handheld (screens in the 6–8" range) can be marketed either as very small laptops or "handheld PCs", while the distinction between the largest laptops (18" or even larger) and "All-in-One" desktops is whether they fold for travel.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Having a higher resolution display can potentially allow more items to fit onscreen at a time, improving the user's ability to multitask, although, at the higher resolutions on smaller screens, the resolution may only serve to display sharper graphics and text rather than increasing the usable area.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Since the introduction of the MacBook Pro with Retina display in 2012, there has been an increase in the availability of "HiDPI" (or high pixel density) displays; as of 2025, this is generally considered to be anything higher than 1920 pixels wide.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] On PC laptops, this is most often 4K (3840-pixel-wide) resolution, although QHD (2560-pixel-wide) resolution is also a common option, and non-standard display resolutions are becoming more frequent.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Most laptop displays have a maximum refresh rate of 60 Hz, although higher refresh rates are common especially on gaming laptops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The Dell M17x and Samsung 700G7A, both released in 2011, were among the first laptops to feature a 120 Hz refresh rate, and more such laptops have appeared in the years since.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Laptop CPUs have advanced power-saving features and produce less heat than those intended for desktop use.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The number of processor cores has generally increased over time, and as of 2025, mainstream laptops can have as few as 6 cores and as many as 16, with high end workstation laptops having as many as 24, and low end or ultra-portable models still being available with 4 cores.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] In many cases, this involves a mix of power-optimized and performance-optimized processor cores.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Laptop processors often have a very broad range in their peak power consumption vs. continuous – typically continuous power is around 15–20 watts on mainstream laptops, 45–60 watts on higher performance models, but these tend to be able to go much higher for short periods.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] By contrast, desktop processors tend to start at a 65W continuous rating with performance models in the 100–120W range being very common, and specialized "high end desktop" and workstation models in some cases exceeding 300W.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] There has been a wide range of CPUs designed for laptops available; as of 2025, the market consists almost entirely of the X86 and ARM architectures.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Major manufacturers include Intel, AMD, Apple and Qualcomm.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] In the past, the PowerPC architecture was also common on Apple laptops (iBook and PowerBook).
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Between around 2000 to 2014, most full-size laptops had socketed, replaceable CPUs; on thinner models, the CPU was soldered on the motherboard and was not replaceable or upgradable without replacing the motherboard.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Since 2015, Intel has not offered new laptop CPU models with pins to be interchangeable, preferring ball grid array chip packages which have to be soldered, and as of 2025 this is true for mainstream laptops from all processor lines.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] In the past, some laptops have used a desktop processor instead of the laptop version, which resulted in higher performance at the cost of much greater weight, heat, and limited battery life.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Since around 2010, the practice has been restricted to small-volume gaming models.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Laptop CPUs are rarely able to be overclocked.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] On most laptops, a GPU is integrated into the CPU to conserve power and space.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] This was introduced by Intel with the Core i-series of mobile processors in 2010, followed by similar AMD APU processors in January 2011.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] On mainstream models, this is typically the only graphics processor.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Higher-end laptops intended for gaming or professional 3D work tend to come with dedicated graphics processors on the motherboard or as an internal expansion card.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Since 2011, these almost always involve switchable graphics so that when there is no demand for the higher performance dedicated graphics processor, the more power-efficient *integrated* graphics processor will be used.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Nvidia Optimus and AMD Hybrid Graphics are examples of this sort of system of switchable graphics.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] In the past, laptops *lacking* a *separate* graphics processor were limited in their utility for gaming and professional applications involving 3D graphics, but the capabilities of CPU-integrated graphics have converged with the low-end of dedicated graphics processors since the mid-2010s.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] For laptops possessing limited onboard graphics capability but sufficient I/O throughput, an external GPU (eGPU) can provide additional graphics power at the cost of physical space and portability.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] As of 2025, whether laptops use removable memory or memory soldered to the motherboard is highly variable.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] When removable, most laptops use SO-DIMM slots in which RAM is mounted.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A new form factor, the CAMM module, has been introduced but has limited market traction.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Before 2000, most laptops used proprietary memory modules if their memory was upgradable.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] When upgradeable, memory slots are sometimes accessible from the bottom of the laptop for ease of upgrading; in other cases, accessing them requires significant disassembly.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Most laptops have two memory slots, although some will have only one, either for cost savings or because some amount of memory is soldered.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] In the past, some high end engineering workstations and gaming laptops had four slots, although this is extremely rare in 2025 with engineering workstations converging on a single CAMM slot.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] As of 2025, 16 GB RAM is most common, with lower-end models occasionally having 8 GB, and 4 GB configurations being limited to a few very-low-cost models.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Higher-end laptops may come with 64 GB of RAM or more.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Laptops usually have built-in speakers and built-in microphones.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] However, integrated speakers may be small and of restricted sound quality to conserve space.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] An alphanumeric keyboard is used to enter text, data, and other commands (e.g., function keys).
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A touchpad (also called a trackpad), a pointing stick, or both, are used to control the position of the cursor on the screen, and an integrated keyboard is used for typing.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Some touchpads have buttons separate from the touch surface, while others share the surface.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A quick double-tap is typically registered as a click, and operating systems may recognize multi-finger touch gestures.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] An external keyboard and mouse may be connected using a USB port or wirelessly, via Bluetooth or similar technology.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Some laptops have multitouch touchscreen displays, either available as an option or standard.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Most laptops have webcams and microphones, which can be used to communicate with other people with both moving images and sound, via web conferencing or video-calling software.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The earliest laptops most often used floppy disks for storage, although a few used either RAM disk or tape.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] By the late 1980s hard disk drives had become the standard form of storage.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Between 1990 and 2009, almost all laptops typically had a hard disk drive (HDD) for storage.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Since around 1990, where a hard drive is present it will typically be a 2.5-inch drive; some very compact laptops support even smaller 1.8-inch HDDs, and a very small number used 1" Microdrives.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] As of 2025, HDDs are essentially extinct in new laptops – although very large capacity drives remain common in desktops and used externally.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] As of 2025, virtually all laptops use NVME solid-state drives for storage, usually in one or more M.2 slots on non-MacOS laptops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Macs have consistently used permanently attached SSDs (integrated with the motherboard) since 2018, and non-removable SSDs are uncommon but not unknown on other manufacturers' laptops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Solid-state drives (SSD) have gradually come to replace hard drives in virtually all cases.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Solid-state drives are faster and more power-efficient, as well as eliminating the hazard of damage or data corruption caused by a laptop's physical impacts, as they use no moving/mechanical parts.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Between their initial introduction around 2008 and the mid-2010s, most SSDs matched the size/shape of a laptop hard drive, but starting around 2014 they have been increasingly replaced with smaller mSATA or M.2 cards.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] In many cases, they are more compact as well.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Initially, in the late 2000s, SSDs were substantially more expensive than HDDs, but prices converged for smaller drives in the late 2010s.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Optical disc drives capable of playing CD-ROMs, compact discs (CD), DVDs, and in some cases, Blu-ray discs (BD), were nearly universal on full-sized models between the mid-1990s and the early 2010s.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] As of 2025, drives are virtually unknown in new laptops, when needed they can be connected via USB instead.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] On a typical laptop, there are several USB ports; if they use only the older USB connectors instead of USB-C, they will typically have an external monitor port (as of 2025, almost always HDMI).
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] An analog audio in/out port (in a combined socket) is common.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Apple, in a 2015 version of its MacBook, transitioned from a number of different I/O ports to a exclusively USB-C ports.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] This port can be used both for charging and connecting a variety of devices through the use of aftermarket adapters.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Apple has since transitioned back to using a number of different ports.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Although common from around 2000 to the early 2010s, built in Ethernet network ports are virtually extinct in mainstream consumer laptops although they can be connected to Ethernet using a USB adapter; they remain built-in in some business and gaming model.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Higher-end systems typically include Thunderbolt ports, which also work as USB-C ports.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A variety of external HDDs or NAS data storage servers with support of RAID technology can be attached to virtually any laptop over such interfaces as USB, FireWire, eSATA, or Thunderbolt, or over a wired or wireless network to further increase space for the storage of data.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Laptops may also incorporate a SD or microSD card slot.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] This enables users to download digital pictures from an SD card onto a laptop, thus enabling them to delete the SD card's contents to free up space for taking new pictures.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] As of 2025, very few laptops support expansion cards, with the primary means of expansion being via USB or Thunderbolt.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] In the past, a PC Card (formerly PCMCIA) or ExpressCard slot for expansion was often present on laptops to allow adding and removing functionality, even when the laptop is powered on.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Mobile PCI Express Module (MXM) is a type of expansion card that is used for graphics cards in some larger, high-end laptops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] As of 2025, laptops are broadly divided between being powered only by USB-C connectors vs. having a dedicated DC power connector; most systems since the mid-2010s that have both connectors can be powered by either.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Dedicated connectors are typically cylindrical/barrel-shaped coaxial power connectors; some vendors such as Lenovo make use of rectangular.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Before the mid-2000s, specialized connectors were much more common.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Most connector heads feature a center pin to allow the end device to determine the power supply type; this can be via a simple protocol like 1-Wire or by measuring the resistance between it and the connector's negative pole (outer surface).
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Vendors may block charging if a power supply is not recognized as the original part, which could deny the legitimate use of universal third-party chargers.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] With the advent of USB-C, portable electronics made increasing use of it for both power delivery and data transfer.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Its support for 20 V (common laptop power supply voltage) and 5 A typically suffices for low to mid-end laptops, but some with higher power demands such as gaming laptops depend on dedicated DC connectors to handle currents beyond 5 A without risking overheating, some even above 10 A.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Additionally, dedicated DC connectors are more durable and less prone to wear and tear from frequent reconnection, as their design is less delicate.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Since the late 1990s, laptops have typically used lithium ion or lithium polymer batteries, These replaced the older nickel metal-hydride typically used throughout most of the 1990s, and nickel–cadmium batteries used in most of the earliest laptops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A few of the oldest laptops used non-rechargeable batteries, or lead–acid batteries.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Battery life is highly variable by model and workload and can range from one hour to nearly a day.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A battery's performance gradually decreases over time; a noticeable reduction in capacity is typically evident after two to three years of regular use, depending on the charging and discharging pattern and the design of the battery.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Innovations in laptops and batteries have seen situations in which the battery can provide up to 24 hours of continued operation, assuming average power consumption levels.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] An example is the HP EliteBook 6930p when used with its ultra-capacity battery.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Laptops with removable batteries may support larger replacement batteries with extended capacity.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A laptop's battery is charged using an external power supply, which is plugged into a wall outlet.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The power supply outputs a DC voltage typically in the range of 7.2—24 volts.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The power supply is usually external and connected to the laptop through a DC connector cable.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] In most cases, it can charge the battery and power the laptop simultaneously.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] When the battery is fully charged, the laptop continues to run on power supplied by the external power supply, avoiding battery use.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] If the used power supply is not strong enough to power computing components and charge the battery simultaneously, the battery may charge in a shorter period of time if the laptop is turned off or sleeping.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The charger typically adds about 400 grams (0.88 lb) to the overall transporting weight of a laptop, although some models are substantially heavier or lighter.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Most 2016-era laptops use a smart battery, a rechargeable battery pack with a built-in battery management system (BMS).
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The smart battery can internally measure voltage and current, and deduce charge level and State of Health (SoH) parameters, indicating the state of the cells.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The highest battery capacity of a laptop ever made is 99.99 watt hour.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The highest charger wattages of laptops include 240 watts for models using USB-C power delivery, and 780 watts for aftermarket models.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Waste heat from the operation is difficult to remove in the compact internal space of a laptop.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The earliest laptops used passive cooling, but since the mid-1990s nearly all mainstream laptops have used fans to use forced air cooling - with significant exceptions for models intended to be extremely thin and light (like some generations of the MacBook Air) or to be very low cost.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Earlier laptops used heat sinks, but since the 2000s, virtually all laptops instead rely on heat pipes or move waste heat towards the edges of the device, to allow for a much smaller and compact fan and heat sink cooling system.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Waste heat is usually exhausted away from the device operator towards the rear or sides of the device.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Multiple air intake paths are used since some intakes can be blocked, such as when the device is placed on a soft conforming surface like a chair cushion.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Secondary device temperature monitoring may reduce performance or trigger an emergency shutdown if it is unable to dissipate heat, such as if the laptop were to be left running and placed inside a carrying case.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Aftermarket cooling pads with external fans can be used with laptops to reduce operating temperatures.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A common accessory for laptops is a laptop sleeve, laptop skin, or laptop case, which provides a degree of protection from scratches.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Sleeves, which are distinguished by being relatively thin and flexible, are most commonly made of neoprene, with sturdier ones made of low-resilience polyurethane.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Some laptop sleeves are wrapped in ballistic nylon to provide some measure of waterproofing.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Bulkier and sturdier cases can be made of metal with polyurethane padding inside and may have locks for added security.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Metal, padded cases also offer protection against impacts and drops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Another common accessory is a laptop cooler, a device that helps lower the internal temperature of the laptop either actively or passively.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A common active method involves using electric fans to draw heat away from the laptop, while a passive method might involve propping the laptop up on some type of pad so it can receive more airflow.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Some stores sell laptop pads that enable a reclining person on a bed to use a laptop.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A docking station (sometimes referred to simply as a *dock*) is a laptop accessory that contains multiple ports and in some cases expansion slots or bays for fixed or removable drives.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A laptop connects and disconnects to a docking station, typically through a single large proprietary connector.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] A docking station is an especially popular laptop accessory in a corporate computing environment, due to the possibility of a docking station transforming a laptop into a full-featured desktop replacement, yet allowing for its easy release.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] This ability can be advantageous to "road warrior" employees who have to travel frequently for work, and yet who also come into the office.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] If more ports are needed, or their position on a laptop is inconvenient, one can use a cheaper passive device known as a port replicator.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] These devices mate to the connectors on the laptop, such as through USB or FireWire.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Laptop charging trolleys, also known as laptop trolleys or laptop carts, are mobile storage containers to charge multiple laptops, netbooks, and tablet computers at the same time.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The trolleys are used in schools that have replaced their traditional static computer labs suites of desktop equipped with "tower" computers, but do not have enough plug sockets in an individual classroom to charge all of the devices.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The trolleys can be wheeled between rooms and classrooms so that all students and teachers in a particular building can access fully charged IT equipment.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Laptop charging trolleys are also used to deter and protect against opportunistic and organized theft.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Schools, especially those with open plan designs, are often prime targets for thieves who steal high-value items.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Laptops, netbooks, and tablets are among the highest–value portable items in a school.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Moreover, laptops can easily be concealed under clothing and stolen from buildings.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Many types of laptop–charging trolleys are designed and constructed to protect against theft.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] They are generally made out of steel, and the laptops remain locked up while not in use.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Although the trolleys can be moved between areas from one classroom to another, they can often be mounted or locked to the floor, support pillars, or walls to prevent thieves from stealing the laptops, especially overnight.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] In some laptops, solar panels are able to generate enough solar power for the laptop to operate.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The One Laptop Per Child Initiative released the OLPC XO-1 laptop which was tested and successfully operated by use of solar panels.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] They were designing an OLPC XO-3 laptop with these features.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] The OLPC XO-3 was planned to operate with 2 watts of electricity.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Samsung has also designed the NC215S solar–powered notebook that was planned to be sold commercially in the U.S. market.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] These are features, hardware, or components that can be found on virtually all laptops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] These are features, hardware, or components that were once very common or completely ubiquitous, have been declining in prominence, but are still widely available among all classes of laptops and can be found on virtually all enterprise-class devices.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] These are features, hardware, or components that were once very common or completely ubiquitous, but are found on almost no new laptops today (if at all).
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Certain modern laptops, like the Panasonic Toughbook line, have continued to maintain support for a few of these features.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Some of the components of earlier models of laptops can easily be replaced without opening completely its bottom part, such as the keyboard, battery, hard disk, memory modules, and CPU cooling fan.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Some of the components of recent models of laptops reside inside.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] Replacing most of its components, such as the keyboard, battery, hard disk, memory modules, CPU cooling fan, etc., requires the removal of either the top or bottom part, the removal of the motherboard, and returning them.
[src:laptop/laptop-p01] In some types, solder and glue are used to mount components such as RAM, storage, and batteries, making repairs additionally difficult.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] The performance of laptops is often worse than comparably priced desktops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] The upper limits of performance of laptops remain lower than desktops, due to mostly practical reasons, such as decreased battery life, increased size and heat, etc.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] The upgradeability of laptops is limited compared to tower desktops, due to technical and economic reasons.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] In general, hard drives and memory can be upgraded easily.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Due to the integrated nature of laptops, however, the motherboard, CPU, and graphics, are seldom officially upgradeable.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] for laptops; Moreover, starting with 2013 models, laptops have become increasingly integrated (soldered) with the motherboard for most of its components (CPU, SSD, RAM, etc.) to reduce size and upgradeability prospects.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Laptops are less durable than desktops/PCs.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] However, the durability of the laptop depends on the user if proper maintenance is done then the laptop can work longer.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Because of their portability, laptops are subject to more wear and physical damage than desktops, additionally hindered by their integrated nature.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] A liquid spill onto the keyboard, while a minor issue with a desktop system, can damage the internals of a laptop and destroy the computer, resulting in a costly repair or entire replacement of laptops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] One study found that a laptop is three times more likely to break during the first year of use than a desktop.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] To maintain a laptop, it is recommended to clean it every three months for dirt, debris, dust, and food particles.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] cloth for the screen and keyboard, compressed air for getting dust out of the cooling fan, and a cleaning solution.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Harsh chemicals such as bleach should not be used to clean a laptop, as they can damage it.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] that can fail from blockage caused by accumulated airborne dust and debris.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Most laptops do not have any type of removable dust collection filter over the air intake for these cooling systems, resulting in a system that gradually conducts more heat and noise as the years pass.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] In some cases, the laptop starts to overheat even at idle load levels.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] This dust is usually stuck inside where the fan and heat sink meet, where it can not be removed by a casual cleaning and vacuuming.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Most of the time, compressed air can dislodge the dust and debris but may not entirely remove it.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] After the device is turned on, the loose debris is reaccumulated into the cooling system by the fans.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Complete disassembly is usually required to clean the laptop entirely.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] However, preventative maintenance such as regular cleaning of the heat sink via compressed air can prevent dust build-up on the heat sink.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] , eventually warranting replacement after as little as 2–3 years.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] A new battery typically stores enough energy to run the laptop for five to six hours or more, depending on usage and the battery size.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] The battery is often easily replaceable and a higher capacity model may be obtained for longer charging and discharging time.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Some laptops do not have the usual removable battery and have to be brought to the service center of their manufacturer or a third-party laptop service center to have their battery replaced.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Replacement batteries can also be expensive, depending on the availability of the parts.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Every day, over 1,600 laptops go missing from U.S. airports.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] , breach of privacy), can be many times the value of the stolen laptop itself.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Consequently, the physical protection of laptops and the safeguarding of data contained in them are both of great importance.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] , which can be used to tether them with a security cable and lock.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] or similar that prevents the use of the device without credentials.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] has been designed to help people locate and recover their stolen laptops in the event of theft.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] however, that number may decrease due to a variety of companies and software solutions specializing in laptop recovery.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] (Eastern District of Pennsylvania 2010), school-issued laptops loaded with special software enabled staff from two high schools to take secret webcam shots of students at home, via their students' laptops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] because of their small, flat keyboard and trackpad pointing devices.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Some health standards require ergonomic keyboards at workplaces.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] A laptop's integrated screen often requires users to lean over for a better view, which can cause neck or spinal injuries.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] A larger and higher-quality external screen can be connected to almost any laptop to alleviate this and to provide additional screen space for more productive work.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] The resulting heat increase, which could not be offset by a laptop cushion, may increase male infertility.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] A common practical solution to this problem is to place the laptop on a table or desk or to use a book or pillow between the body and the laptop.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Another solution is to obtain a cooling unit for the laptop.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] – which results in the laptop remaining cool to the touch, and greatly reduces laptop heat buildup.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] There are many laptop brands and manufacturers.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Several major brands that offer notebooks in various classes are listed in the adjacent box.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] The major brands usually offer good service and support, including well-executed documentation and driver downloads that remain available for many years after a particular laptop model is no longer produced.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Capitalizing on service, support, and brand image, laptops from major brands are more expensive than laptops from smaller brands and ODMs.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Some brands specialize in a particular class of laptops, such as gaming laptops (Alienware), high-performance laptops (HP Envy), netbooks (EeePC) and laptops for children (OLPC).
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Many brands, including the major ones, do not design and do not manufacture their laptops.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Instead, a small number of Original Design Manufacturers (ODMs) design new models of laptops, and the brands choose the models to be included in their lineup.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] In 2006, 7 major ODMs manufactured 7 of every 10 laptops in the world, with the largest one (Quanta Computer) having 30% of the world market share.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Therefore, identical models are available both from a major label and from a low-profile ODM in-house brand.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] As of 1989 Zenith Data Systems, Toshiba, Compaq, and Grid Systems were the leading vendors of a market that *InfoWorld* described as "small but vital".
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] As of 1992–1993, Toshiba ranked as the global leading vendor in the notebook computer market.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] In the United States meanwhile, Apple led the market followed by Compaq.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] In the year 1993, global revenue for the laptop market was led by Compaq, followed by Toshiba, Apple, NEC and IBM, altogether accounting for over 53% of global revenue.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] In the United States, the top three vendors for notebooks in market share as of 1996 were: Toshiba, followed by Compaq, and followed by IBM.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] As of 1999, Toshiba ranked first in worldwide laptop sales followed by IBM, Compaq, and Dell.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Toshiba led the market with a share of 18.6%.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] In the first quarter of 2002 in the United States market, Dell controlled 25.2% in the notebook space, well ahead of Toshiba (13.6%) and Compaq (11.7%), the latter of which had been acquired by Hewlett-Packard (HP).
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] At fourth and fifth place were Sony and IBM.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] In Europe, the Middle East and Africa (EMEA) territories, Acer was the largest vendor of laptops, in 2004–2005, having overtaken HP and IBM there.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] In the year 2005 according to IDC, Dell was the top global vendor of notebooks with a market share of 17.29%, followed by: HP (15.7%), Toshiba (10.96%), Acer (10.15%) and Lenovo (8.23%); Lenovo had acquired IBM that same year.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] The remaining of the top ten was made up of Fujitsu Siemens, Sony, NEC, Apple and Asus.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] In the first quarter of 2010, the largest vendor of portable computers, including netbooks, was either HP or Acer, depending on data source.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Both had shipped approximately 9 million units each.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Dell, Toshiba, Asus and Lenovo followed, each with approximate sales of 5 to 6 million each.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Apple, Samsung and Sony sold under 2 million each.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] As of the third quarter of 2020, HP was cited as the leading vendor for notebook computers closely followed by Lenovo, both with a share of 23.6% each.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Battery-powered portable computers had just 2% worldwide market share in 1986.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] However, laptops have become increasingly popular, both for business and personal use.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] The third quarter of 2008 was the first time when worldwide notebook PC shipments exceeded desktops, with 38.6 million units versus 38.5 million units.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] In 2023, it was estimated that 166 million laptops were sold, and in the first quarter of 2024, around 64% of personal computers sold were laptops or detachable tablets.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Due to the advent of tablets and affordable laptops, many computer users now have laptops due to the convenience offered by the device.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Before 2008, laptops were very expensive.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] In May 2005, the average notebook sold for $1,131 while desktops sold for an average of $696.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Around 2008, however, prices of laptops decreased substantially due to low-cost netbooks, drawing an average US$689 at U.S. retail stores in August 2008.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Starting with the 2010s, laptops have decreased substantially in price at the low end due to inexpensive and low power Arm processors, less demanding operating systems such as ChromeOS, and SoC's.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] As of 2023, a new laptop can be obtained for $299.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] The list of materials that go into a laptop computer is long, and many of the substances used, such as beryllium, lead, chromium, and mercury compounds, are toxic or carcinogenic to humans.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Although these toxins are relatively harmless when the laptop is in use, concerns that discarded laptops cause a serious health and environmental risks when improperly discarded have arisen.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] The Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment Directive (WEEE Directive) in Europe specified that all laptop computers must be recycled by law.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) has outlawed landfill dumping or the incinerating of discarded laptop computers.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Most laptop computers begin the recycling process with a method known as Demanufacturing, which involves the physical separation of the components of the laptop.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] These components are then either grouped into materials (e.g. plastic, metal and glass) for recycling or more complex items that require more advanced materials separation (e.g.) circuit boards, hard drives and batteries.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Corporate laptop recycling can require an additional process known as data destruction.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] The data destruction process ensures that all information or data that has been stored on a laptop hard drive can never be retrieved again.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] The ruggedized Grid Compass computer was used since the early days of the Space Shuttle program.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] The first commercial laptop used in space was a Macintosh portable in 1990 on Space Shuttle mission STS-41 and again in 1991 aboard STS-43.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Apple and other laptop computers continue to be flown aboard crewed spaceflights, though the only long-duration flight certified computer for the International Space Station is the ThinkPad.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] As of 2011, over 100 ThinkPads were aboard the ISS.
[src:laptop/laptop-p02] Laptops operating in harsh usage environments and conditions, such as strong vibrations, extreme temperatures, and wet or dusty conditions differ from those used in space in that they are custom designed for the task and do not use commercial off-the-shelf hardware.
